  <!--
    No reviewed suppressions are needed here. This module's whole subject is the source-level style/
    convention gate (Checkstyle), and it is held to the bytecode gate (SpotBugs) only to demonstrate the
    chapter's point that a Checkstyle-clean module is not thereby correct — the two analyzers read the
    program at different points (Chapter 16). The Java is written to keep SpotBugs quiet on its own merits
    (prices held as integer cents, defensive copies, no exposed internal arrays), so the filter is empty.

    A genuine, reviewed false positive would be named here narrowly — by class, method, and pattern — with
    a reason, exactly as the Chapter 26 module does. It would never be handled by disabling a detector
    wholesale. The Checkstyle side shows the complementary per-site control: the
    @SuppressWarnings("checkstyle:ConstantName") on PriceFormatter records one reviewed exception in code.
  -->
</FindBugsFilter>
